 include lived religion—the daily practices of ordinary people. Seeing religion around Benjamin requires looking at forms of life and institutions that he rarely discussed. As Britt shows, dramatic changes in religious practices, particularly in Berlin, reflected broader political and cultural currents that would soon transform the lives of all Europeans.An original perspective on the religious context of a thinker who habitually raised questions about the survival of religion in modernity, Religion Around Walter Benjamin contributes to wider discussions of religious tradition and secular modernity in religious and cultural studies. It provides a foundational overview and introduction to the context of Benjamin’s writing that will be appreciated by scholars and students alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJewish philosophersy20th centuryvBiography. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aBenjamin’s secularism.  aWeimar.  alived religion.  apolitical theology.  areligious context of Walter Benjamin.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076692940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271093574?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271093574423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271093574/original  a978-3-11-076692-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles